StressorDescription: TG and I recently had a baby together. I'll call her IG. IG is almost 5 months old, and having a new baby around has been a really big adjustment. TG and I have been a really great team as we've transitioned into being new parents, but naturally, bringing a whole new person in to the mix is going to cause some conflict. Our biggest conflict recently has been regarding how to manage taking care of a baby while also keeping our house somewhat clean and clutter-free. We are sleep deprived, I'm working a full time job, and he's a freelancer. Any time I'm not with IG, he takes her, but being so overworked and tired means that our house cleaning often falls through the cracks. Recently, he shared with me that he's a bit stressed out because there's a lot of clutter around the house and there's really no place that is fully clean. I was a little frustrated with this because I'm working full time and caring for a baby, and I tend to contribute more to house cleaning than he does, but we talked it out and ultimately came to the conclusion that we'd create a daily cleaning schedule. I think the reason we had this conflict was because there's so much change in our life that we were overhwelmed with the smaller tasks involved with cleaning, and making this schedule has already helped us each balance our responsibilities and keep things from being too messy.
RSTask: The absolute best thing about my relationship is how supportive and caring TG is. I can pretty much always rely on him to support me through all of my struggles, and I never fear that he doesn't love me. I really have never met anyone as supportive as he is. I'm a pretty anxious person, but knowing that he will always have my back is so helpful and makes me feel secure in our relationship.

This conflict shows me how much AH cares about it. In a sense, it shows they are worried about losing me. This makes me feel wanted and desired. However it makes me feel a bit guilty for their insecurity causing me a sense of security.

StressorDescription: My mother had recently lost an ex partner very suddenly. She tends to be fairly emotionally closed off despite being an emotional person who is sensitive in many ways. It was a difficult thing to contend with because I wanted her to know she was supported by me and I wanted to provide a safe space for her to open up and emote about and process the event. She was initially making light of it and using that comedic or flippant behavior to more easily cope with the loss. I tried to treat her like herself not like the version of her I wish for because I know she processes traumatic events the way she does for very valid reasons. Instead of being critical or impatient with her, I asked her if she would reach out to me whenever she was in the mood to chat which she fairly often is. Eventually I caught her at an open time and she was very forthcoming with stories, emotions, regrets, musings, and reflections about her ex partner and it was cathartic for both of us, I think.
PRTask: I certainly count this experience as one that helped me and will continue to help me more deeply understand my mother. In addition, it gives me an opportunity to support her emotionally and hopefully model a healthy emotional interaction for her and with her. She doesn't really believe its valuable to deeply reflect and allow sadness in but in my opinion, this is vital to the healing and understanding process of life's troubles and circumstances; both big and small, personal and impersonal. I think opening this door will deepen our relationship and our conversations and hopefully she will continue to open up to me and use me in a healthy way as a supportive sounding board for her.

StressorDescription: Just this morning, CB and I had an argument while trying to set up a surveillance camera. I thought that was obviously what they were doing, and tried to explain that, but before I could get anything out, CB closed out of what they were doing on their phone, disconnected the camera and threw it down on the bed, exclaming "Well I'm not gonna do this right now, I have other things to do". They felt attacked because I made them feel like their answer of "trying to set this camera up" was not good enough, and that I didn't trust them. I admitted they were right, that I didn't trust them, (due to a series of events over the last year or so, that include a whole bunch of lying and webcamming with other people), but that I wanted to, and that by involving them in the set up of this surveillance camera, I was trying to give them a chance. StressorDescription: Due to supply issues at my place of employment, I have been home a lot more. RT asked me if I would be home the next day because he needed to order groceries and have them delivered; he didn't want frozen food thawing out before he got home. I told him I would be. I ended up going in overnight to my job and didn't get home until 5am. I went to bed but made sure I woke up early because I was expecting a delivery at some point. I stayed up all day, exhausted, waiting for this grocery delivery. When he came home around 3pm, I asked him what happened with the groceries because they never came. He said, "Oh, I scheduled them for later tonight." I asked him why did he ask me if I was going to be home if he was going to order them later in the day and he said he wasn't sure if I'd actually be home so he thought it was easier. Historically, if he asks me that, he puts the order in for the morning so I had no reason to believe that it wouldn't be happening and I would have slept had I known so I was pretty upset. This turned into a conversation about how he doesn't communicate with me about his plans (e.g., he left for the majority of July without telling me he had planned to do so). I found it really frustrating and inconsiderate, especially when he didn't initially think it was a big deal because if the tables were turned, he wouldn't have stayed up for my groceries. I should've verified there was an actual delivery but I didn't think it was necessary since I said I would be home.

I am going to SF for a show and originally I was going to drive myself but now I have a sudden funeral the night before in a different state. He rearranged his schedule to make sure he could pick me up from the airport and get me to the show. I thought I would have to cancel the show which was postponed for two years but he's helping me make it happen.

During the lockdowns I stayed with them so that I could run their errands and keep their spirits up.  My staying with them was temporary, I have my own home.  I have friends and I need to find work.  I want to get another dog.  I don't have a big life but it is my own independent life.  Since I moved back home I have been pressured every few months or so to come live with them full time.  I had several conversations where I explained that moving into their basement would mean that I am giving up on having a life outside of my relationship with them.  They require all of my focus when i am there.  They are also very traditional, so I would not be able to date, I would not be able to have people over.  I also wouldn't be able to get another dog.  I miss my girl.  She died in 2019 and I'm ready for another pet.  My mom says she understands and we go along happily, then she'll bring it up again.  I feel unheard, I feel unimportant.
